      "The Berkeley is the Maybourne group's third sibling, completing the trio with Claridge's and The Connaught. Same ownership, same operating standard, positioned deliberately as the contemporary modernist counterweight to the two Mayfair grand dames. Where Claridge's leans Art Deco and the Connaught leans late-Victorian, the Berkeley leans mid-century modernist and has resisted attempts to make it look like the other two.",
      "The hotel's most unusual amenity, for central London, is its seventh-floor outdoor rooftop pool. The pool is heated, covered by a retractable roof in winter, and looks across Knightsbridge rooftops to Hyde Park. No other central London grand hotel has an outdoor pool, which makes the Berkeley the only option for swimming-focused city stays. The pool is reserved for hotel guests.",
      "The Knightsbridge location defines the hotel's clientele. Harrods is four minutes' walk. Harvey Nichols is two. The Sloane Street flagship retail strip (Dior, Hermes, Saint Laurent, Chanel) starts at the hotel's door. For guests whose visit to London is primarily shopping-focused, the Berkeley is geographically the most efficient of the grand hotels, including over the Mayfair options. Hyde Park is three minutes north.",
      "The culinary program recently shifted. The long-running Marcus Wareing restaurant, Marcus at The Berkeley, closed in 2022, replaced by La Môme London, an offshoot of the Saint-Tropez original, opened in 2023. Cedric Grolet at The Berkeley, the London outpost of the French pastry chef's Parisian patisserie (Cedric Grolet Opéra), occupies the ground-floor daytime space. The Blue Bar, designed by David Collins in 2000, is one of London's most photographed hotel bars, notable for its deep blue-painted panelling.",
      "The Collins Room serves what is probably London's most conceptually distinctive afternoon tea: Prêt-à-Portea, a fashion-themed service where the patisserie is shaped as miniature versions of current-season couture from a rotating selection of designers (Chanel, Dior, Balenciaga, and so on). It has run since 2005 and books out weeks in advance. Taste applies; people either find it delightful or find it a novelty that outstays its welcome. Either view is defensible.",
      "The rooms, refurbished in 2016, follow the Maybourne contemporary-luxury vocabulary: muted palettes, bespoke furniture, higher ceilings than Claridge's, more natural light because of the 1972 building. Some rooms overlook the pool; the Park-facing rooms on higher floors look across Wilton Place to Hyde Park.",
      "The Berkeley suits guests who want a pool, prioritise Knightsbridge shopping, or prefer a more contemporary design vocabulary than the Victorian and Edwardian grand hotels offer. It does not suit anyone who wants the continuous-heritage-building feel that Claridge's or The Connaught provide, nor anyone looking for an independent rather than group-operated hotel.",
