    architectureHistory: "The building at 8 Balderton Street was designed by Wimperis and Simpson in 1926 as Macy's Garage, which served the neighbouring Selfridges department store for deliveries and as a rank for the store's fleet of private cars. The building's Art Deco facade was designed at a scale and quality unusual for a service building, which is part of why it has survived. It holds Grade II listed status. In 2014, hoteliers Jeremy King and Chris Corbin (Wolseley, Delaunay) opened The Beaumont within the converted building, in partnership with the Barclay family. The 2023 refurbishment added a new wing, expanding the room count from 73 to 101 keys. The hotel's defining architectural feature, ROOM, a four-storey cubist sculpture by Antony Gormley projecting from the front facade, contains a functional hotel suite inside its bronze-clad interior; the Gormley installation was commissioned and constructed as part of the 2014 conversion.",
    brief: [
      "The Beaumont is the most recent hotel in this list to have entered the London grand category, and it entered it quickly. Opened in 2014 by Jeremy King and Chris Corbin, the restaurateurs behind The Wolseley and The Delaunay, the hotel positioned itself as a 1920s transatlantic liner transplanted to Mayfair: Art Deco vocabulary throughout, American-steakhouse culinary register, a deliberately theatrical sense of mid-century glamour. Within three years of opening it had secured its place alongside the older grand hotels.",
      "The building is the starting point. Wimperis and Simpson's 1926 Art Deco garage, built to service Selfridges, is an unlikely candidate for a grand hotel, and the conversion worked hard to preserve the building's industrial bones while inserting the hotel's theatrical interior. The Art Deco facade is original. The ground-floor vehicle entrance is now the arrival court. The interior, designed by ReardonSmith Architects with Alexandra Champalimaud, is period-accurate to the late 1920s: black and white marble, brass, ebonised wood, leather-upholstered banquettes.",
      "The hotel's single most-photographed feature is ROOM, the Antony Gormley sculpture that projects from the front of the building across four storeys. Clad in fumed oak externally, the interior is a crouching anthropomorphic space (modelled on Gormley's own body at rest) with a double bed, a shower, and a small reading chair. The suite is bookable, and guests who stay in it sleep inside a functioning Turner Prize-winning sculpture. It is, as far as we know, the only hotel suite in the world that is also a publicly installed artwork. The rate is typically two to three times the hotel's standard suite rate.",
      "The Colony Grill Room, the hotel's restaurant, is a full-bore 1920s-New-York chop house: steaks, oysters, Waldorf salad, lobster Thermidor, all served by tuxedoed waiters. It is one of the more consistent restaurant rooms in Mayfair and does not pretend to be anything more than what it is. Afternoon tea is served here rather than in a separate tea room. The two bars, Le Magritte Bar and The American Bar, carry the same Deco register.",
      "The 2023 expansion added a new wing and shifted the hotel's character somewhat. The new rooms and suites are slightly more contemporary in their vocabulary while remaining within the Deco framework. The Beaumont Spa, part of the expansion, is compact but well-specified; the hotel does not have a pool.",
      "The location is Mayfair's commercial edge, on the Oxford Street side rather than the Piccadilly side. Selfridges is two minutes' walk. Bond Street station is three. Grosvenor Square and Mount Street are five. Hyde Park is eight. Brown Hart Gardens, the raised public garden square that the hotel faces, is one of central London's more unexpected spaces: built over an electrical substation in 1906, it is elevated above street level and surrounded by Edwardian terraces. The hotel's rooms overlook this square on the quieter side.",
      "The Beaumont suits guests who want a design-led hotel with a genuine decorative vision rather than a generic contemporary-luxury vocabulary, who appreciate American-style service and dining, or who specifically want to stay in an Antony Gormley sculpture. It does not suit anyone who wants the quiet residential feel of Carlos Place or Brook Street; the Oxford Street edge of Mayfair is busier.",
    ],
    stayWardNote: "The Beaumont operates rate parity with major booking channels, with the standard OTA carve-out for private rates offered to individual travellers. Because the Beaumont is independently owned (Barclay family) rather than part of a large group, its pricing is less tightly managed than the Maybourne or Dorchester Collection properties, which typically means more flexibility. Private rates we have been quoted on shoulder-season midweek dates have typically landed 12 to 20 per cent below the public parity rate. The ROOM suite specifically is never discounted and is frequently booked out weeks in advance; we can put you on a wait list via the hotel if desired. Not guaranteed.",
